Correct me if I'm wrong, but if I recall my physics lessons correctly, resonance has little to do with the speed of rotation of an object**, and more about the natural frequency of vibration for that object, which is linked to (1) its length, and (2) the speed of a wave traveling through that object (the latter affected by object composition, e.g. aluminum, steel, etc.; its stiffness/thickness, i.e. the stiffer it is the faster it'll travel; and its mass, i.e. the heavier the slower the traveling wave will be). Actually, the length would be a pretty major factor since it...Read moreCorrect me if Iâ€™m wrong, but if I recall my physics lessons correctly, resonance has little to do with the speed of rotation of an object**, and more about the natural frequency of vibration for that object, which is linked to (1) its length, and (2) the speed of a wave traveling through that object (the latter affected by object composition, e.g. aluminum, steel, etc.; its stiffness/thickness, i.e. the stiffer it is the faster itâ€™ll travel; and its mass, i.e. the heavier the slower the traveling wave will be). Actually, the length would be a pretty major factor since it would dictate which frequency an object is â€œvulnerableâ€ to by resonance; alter its length and the â€œattackâ€ frequency no longer has any effect. Make any sense?
So, for a laptop HDD, for the length we would start with 2.5â€³ (so says http://209.68.14.80/ref/hdd/op/mediaSize-c.html) *minus* the diameter of the platterâ€™s machined inner hole, with that measure then divided by 2 (i.e. the platter being a 2D annulus, the width of one of the two â€œbandsâ€ when you cut the annulus in half through its center).
But I wouldnâ€™t have a clue as to the natural frequency of a single 2.5â€³ HDD platter; either it needs to be determined experimentally, or else there may be tables for common materials (with given density) by their thickness (or engineering software stacks/packages capable of computing them).
So, itâ€™s probably more complicated than 5400RPM = 90 Hz.
